      "question": "Find the value of $k$ for which the quadratic equation $(k-2)x^2 + 2(2k-3)x + (5k-6) = 0$ has equal roots. Hence, find the value of the roots.",
      "answer": "$k = 2$ or $k = 3$; If $k = 3$, roots are $-3, -3$. (Note: $k=2$ is rejected as the equation becomes linear $2x = -4$)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the coefficients $a = k-2$, $b = 2(2k-3)$, and $c = 5k-6$ from the standard form $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$.",
          "For equal roots, the discriminant $D = b^2 - 4ac$ must be equal to $0$.",
          "Substitute the coefficients into the discriminant formula and simplify to form a quadratic in $k$.",
          "Solve for $k$ and check the validity of each value in the original equation, then substitute the valid $k$ to find the roots."
        ],
        "derivation": "$D = [2(2k-3)]^2 - 4(k-2)(5k-6) = 0 \\\\ 4(4k^2 - 12k + 9) - 4(5k^2 - 6k - 10k + 12) = 0 \\\\ 16k^2 - 48k + 36 - 20k^2 + 64k - 48 = 0 \\\\ -4k^2 + 16k - 12 = 0 \\\\ k^2 - 4k + 3 = 0 \\\\ (k-1)(k-3) = 0 \\\\ k = 1, k = 3 \\\\ \\text{If } k=3, (3-2)x^2 + 2(6-3)x + (15-6) = 0 \\Rightarrow x^2 + 6x + 9 = 0 \\Rightarrow (x+3)^2 = 0 \\Rightarrow x = -3 \\\\ \\text{If } k=1, (1-2)x^2 + 2(2-3)x + (5-6) = 0 \\Rightarrow -x^2 - 2x - 1 = 0 \\Rightarrow x^2 + 2x + 1 = 0 \\Rightarrow x = -1$"
      },
